00:20:32.560 --> 00:20:36.479
You can post to it. You can interact with it. And it feels great.

00:20:39.119 --> 00:20:43.040
But then, you know, you might have to do some analysis on your model. You might do some

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:48.239
monitoring. You might have some weird instance or just any other ad hoc information that you need

00:20:48.239 --> 00:20:52.880
to get from your model. And now you don't have to peek into that Docker container anymore.

00:20:52.880 --> 00:21:00.560
You can just load it right from your pins board right into memory and use it as expected. You

00:21:00.560 --> 00:21:07.599
can do all your analysis on your model. And that kind of completes our cycle here.

00:21:08.560 --> 00:21:14.640
We have our model is versioned with pins. It's deployed. It's either running in Connect

00:21:15.199 --> 00:21:19.119
with a one liner or you've made a Docker file to bring it to some other public cloud.

00:21:20.239 --> 00:21:27.359
And now it's time to monitor. Because once a model is deployed, a data scientist's work is not done.

00:21:28.479 --> 00:21:33.119
I do have to say here that monitoring in this sense is going to be a little bit different than

00:21:33.119 --> 00:21:39.680
maybe you're used to. We're not particularly interested in this package at looking at,

00:21:39.680 --> 00:21:46.560
like, CPU usage or runtime. Here we're looking at statistical methods. So, like, RSME, MAE,

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:53.119
like, is your model performing as well as you thought it was or expect it to?

00:21:54.160 --> 00:21:59.920
And Vennover has some helper functions to help you compute pin and plot metrics. I'm not going

00:21:59.920 --> 00:22:04.959
to give you, like, too in depth of these, but just know they exist. They help you do things

00:22:04.959 --> 00:22:11.760
like store your metrics data and handles that awkward, like, I have a few days that overlap.

00:22:11.760 --> 00:22:18.319
You can choose if it overwrites on the last export or not. And a one liner that helps you

00:22:18.319 --> 00:22:22.239
plot the metrics using Plotly to get all that lovely interactivity.

00:22:22.959 --> 00:22:28.800
And I think this is super important to say explicitly, but you should probably be monitoring

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:35.839
your model if it's deployed. And that's because, you know, data science is it's a little funky.

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:43.920
If things go wrong, you don't necessarily get an error message. You don't get that big X,

00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:49.680
like, cannot compile, things are failing. Like, your model can continue to give you

00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:54.640
answers, even if it's 0% accuracy. Like, even if it's the worst model in existence,

00:22:54.640 --> 00:22:59.280
it will confidently give you that answer. And if you're not monitoring, you might think that

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:04.479
answer is right. So, it's super important. Because if you're not monitoring your model,

00:23:04.479 --> 00:23:13.520
you are oblivious to decay. And that completes our cycle. We can version deploy and monitor models.

